    "summary": "The Nara Period (710–794 AD) was Japan's first era of fully consolidated imperial government — named for the new capital city of Nara, modeled on the Tang Chinese capital Chang'an, that was Japan's first permanent capital city. Under emperors who governed through Tang-inspired legal codes (the Taiho Code of 701 AD), Japan experienced a comprehensive Sinification: Chinese-style bureaucracy, Buddhist state religion, Chinese writing, and Chinese artistic traditions all became central to Japanese court culture. The great Buddhist temples of Nara — the Todai-ji (completed 752 AD, housing a 15-meter bronze Buddha, the largest bronze statue ever cast), the Kofuku-ji, and the Horyu-ji — testify to the intensity of imperial Buddhist patronage.\n\nThe Nara period also saw the compilation of Japan's first written histories: the Kojiki (712 AD) and Nihon Shoki (720 AD), recording imperial mythology and history in Chinese-style literary form. The Man'yoshu — the oldest anthology of Japanese poetry, compiled c. 759 AD — collected over 4,500 poems in the Japanese vernacular (using Chinese characters phonetically), including the oldest surviving Japanese poetry. The period ended with the court's move to a new capital (eventually Kyoto/Heian-kyo in 794 AD) to escape the growing political power of Nara's Buddhist temples, which had become so wealthy and influential that monks were attempting to control imperial succession — a reminder of the fine line between state religion and clerical power.",
